<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-regular-polygons">
    <title>Area of Regular Polygons</title>
     <introduction>
     <p>
        â™¦ There are several ways to describe polygons. One is the regularity or irregularity of sides and angles.
     </p>
     <p>
        â™¦ A polygon is <m>\textbf{regular}</m> when all of it's sides and angles are equal. All the sides and all the angles are equal making it regular.
     </p>
     <p>
        â™¦ In a regular polygon we can work out the area of the polgon by working out the area of one triangle then multiply by the number of similar triangles formed by the polygon. For example how many triangles can we have from an hexagon? 
     </p>
     <p>
        â™¦ The <m>\textbf{area}</m> of a <m>\textbf{regular polygon}</m> can be found using this formula, where <m>\textbf{P}</m>
        is the <m>\textbf{perimeter}</m> and <m>\textbf{a}</m>
        is the apothem
     </p>
      <p>
        The <m>\textbf{apothem}</m> is the distance from the center of a regular polygon to <m>\, \textbf{a} </m>side. Where <m> \textbf{a}</m> is the half <m>\frac{1}{2} \text{side.}</m>
     </p>
     <image width="50%">
     <latex-image label="polgon-triangle">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
                    
            % Define colors
            \definecolor{hexcolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light blue fill
            \definecolor{edgecolor}{RGB}{30, 144, 255}  % Blue outline

            % Define hexagon vertices
            \def\R{3} % Radius of hexagon
            \foreach \i in {0,60,...,300} {
                \coordinate (P\i) at (\i:\R);
            }

            % Draw the hexagon
            \filldraw[fill=hexcolor, draw=edgecolor, thick] 
                (P0) -- (P60) -- (P120) -- (P180) -- (P240) -- (P300) -- cycle;

            % Define center
            \coordinate (C) at (0,0);
            
            % Draw the perpendicular segment
            \draw[dashed] (C) -- (0,-2.62) node[midway,left] {\Large $a$};

            % Right angle marker
            \draw[thick] (0,-2.35) -- (0.2,-2.35) -- (0.2,-2.62);
            % \draw (0,-\R)++(0,0) -- ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.);

            % Mark the center point
            \filldraw[black] (C) circle (2pt);
        \end{tikzpicture}
     </latex-image>
     </image>
    
     <p>
        You want to find the area of the triangle. You can see it has an apothem of
        <m>\sqrt{3}</m> meters and a side length of 10 meters.

     </p>
     <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="polgon-hexagon">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Define triangle vertices
                \coordinate (A) at (-3,0);
                \coordinate (B) at (3,0);
                \coordinate (C) at (0,6); % Height of an equilateral triangle with side 6

                % Draw the equilateral triangle
                \draw[thick, blue] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
            
                % Label the side length
                \draw[thick,blue] (A) -- node[left] {\Large 10 m} (C);
            
                % Define point E inside the triangle
                \coordinate (E) at (0,2.2);
                \coordinate (E1) at (1.5,3);
            
                % Draw perpendicular segment from E to side BC
                \draw[dashed] (E) -- (E1) node[above ,midway,rotate=40] {\large $\sqrt{3}$ m};
            
                %draw the right angle
                \tkzMarkRightAngle[draw=black,size=.2](B,E1,E);
            
                % Label the perpendicular length
            
                % Label point E
                \node[left] at (E) {\Large $A$};
                \filldraw[black] (E) circle (2pt);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
     </image>
        <p>
            If you also find the perimeter, P
,
        then you can use the formula A= <m> \frac{1}{2} \textbf{P}a</m> to find the area.
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                \textbf{P} = \text{length of each side } \times a \text{, where } a = h
            </me>
            
            <me>
                P = 10 \, \text{m} \times 3
            </me>
            <me>
                = 30, \text{m}
            </me>
            Now, use the formula for the area of a regular polygon is :
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> A = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 30 \times \sqrt{3} </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 125.98 \, \text{m}^2 </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A regular hexagon with center h is shown below
                </p>
                <p>
                 Similarly you can use <m>A = \frac{1}{2} \times n \times S \times a</m>
                </p>   
               
                <image width="60%">
     <latex-image label="polgon-hexagon-example">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
             \definecolor{hexcolor}{RGB}{102, 255, 102} % Light blue fill
            \definecolor{edgecolor}{RGB}{30, 144, 255}  % Blue outline

            % Define hexagon vertices
            \def\R{3} % Radius of hexagon
            \foreach \i in {0,60,...,300} {
                \coordinate (P\i) at (\i:\R);
            }

            % Draw the hexagon
            \filldraw[fill=hexcolor, draw=edgecolor, thick] 
                (P0) -- (P60) -- (P120) -- (P180) -- (P240) -- (P300) -- cycle;

            % Define center
            \coordinate (C) at (0,0) node[above] {\Large h};
            
            % Draw the perpendicular segment
            \draw[dashed] (C) -- (0,-2.62) node[midway,left] {\Large $14$ cm};

            % Right angle marker
            \draw[thick] (0,-2.35) -- (0.2,-2.35) -- (0.2,-2.62) node[below]{20 cm};
            % \draw (0,-\R)++(0,0) -- ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.);

            % Mark the center point
            \filldraw[black] (C) circle (2pt);
           
        \end{tikzpicture}
     </latex-image>
     </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                     <p>Find the perimeter P, Then use the formula A= <m> \frac{1}{2} \textbf{P}a</m> to find the area.
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                \textbf{P} = \text{length of each side } \times a
            </me>
            
            <me>
                P = 20 \, \text{cm} \times 6
            </me>
            <me>
                = 120 \, \text{cm}^2
            </me>
            Now, use the formula for the area of a regular polygon is :
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> A = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 120 \times 14 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 840 \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
         <p>
                    Where <m>n = \text{number of sides,} S = \text{length of each side and } a = \frac{S}{2}  </m>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A = \amp  \frac{1}{2} n \times S \times a</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp  \frac{1}{2} \times 6 \times 20 \, \text{cm} \times 14 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{1,680}{2} \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 840 \,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
      </introduction> 

<subsubsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-an-Heptagon">
    <title>Area of Heptagon</title>
    <p>
         A heptagon is a seven-sided polygon. It has seven edges and seven vertices.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\textbf{Objective:}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                learners are expected to know how to construct a regular heptagon (7-sided polygon) using a compass, ruler, and protractor.
            </p>
            <p>
              Materials Needed:  
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Materials Needed: </p>
                         <p> â™¦ Compass</p>
                             <p> â™¦  Ruler</p>
                            <p> â™¦  Protractor</p>
                            <p>â™¦  Pencil</p>
                                   
                                    
                                    
                                    <p>â™¦  Eraser</p>  
                             <p>â™¦  Graph paper (optional)</p>
                       
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Step:1 Draw a Circle.
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>                
                                      Place the compass pointer on the paper and draw a circle of any radius. 
                                    
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                       Mark the center (O) of the circle. 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Step 2: Draw a Horizontal Diameter
                        <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Use the ruler to draw a straight line measuring 10cm through the center (O), creating a diameter (A
                                        0 to P1).
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Label the first point P1 on the circumference.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Step 3: Divide the Circle into Seven Equal Parts
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Use a protractor to measure angles of 360Â° Ã· 7 = 51.43Â° from point P1.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Mark each 51.43Â° interval around the circle to get seven points.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Step 4: Connect the Points as shown below.
                             <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Use the ruler to draw straight lines connecting the seven points in sequence.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        The heptagon is now complete! 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="regular-heptagon">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the heptagon
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:2);
                    }
                    
                    % Fill the heptagon with pink color
                    \fill[green!10] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the heptagon
                    \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Label the vertices
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \node[font=\small] at ({360/7*\i}:2.2) {$P_{\i}$};
                    }
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
                        <p>
                           <m> \textbf{Extended Activity.}</m>
                       </p>                        
                        <p>
                            ðŸ”¹ Try drawing a heptagon using only a compass (without a protractor)
                        </p>
                    
                        <p>
                            ðŸ”¹ Shade the inside of the heptagon with different colors to make a pattern.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ”¹ Find the sum of the interior angles of the heptagon. (<m>Hint: (n-2) \times 180^\circ</m>)
                        </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Discussion Questions}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                 1. What is the sum of all interior angles of a heptagon? 
            </p>
            <p>
                 2. How do we calculate the measure of one interior angle of a regular heptagon? 
            </p>
            <p>
                 3. Can you find a heptagon in real life (architecture, logos, etc.)?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m> {\color{blue}\textbf{Properties of a Regular Heptagon.}}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
       â™¦ Sum of interior angles = <m> (n-2) \times 180^\circ</m>. Where n is the number of sides.
    </p>
    <p>
       â™¦ Example for a Heptagon (7-sided polygon).
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
          (n-2) \times 180^\circ  
        </me>
        <me>
            (7-2) \times 180^\circ = 900^\circ
        </me>      
    </p>
    <p>
       â™¦ Sum of exterior angles of any <m>\textbf{polygon(regular or irregular)}</m> is always equl to <m>360^\circ</m> for both regular and irregular polygons.
    </p>
    <p>
        â™¦ Each Interior and Exterior Angle (Regular Polygon Only)
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
        \textbf{Each Interior Angle (for a regular polygon):}    
        </me>
        <me>
            Interior Angle = \frac{(n-2) \times 180^\circ}{n}
        </me>
        <me>
            \textbf{Each Exterior Angle (for a regular polygon):}
        </me>
        <me>
            Exterior Angle = \frac{360^ \circ}{n}
        </me>
    </p>
    <p>
       â™¦  Example for a Regular Heptagon:
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
            \textbf{Each Interior Angle} = \frac{900}{7}
        </me>
        <me>
            = 128.57^ \circ
        </me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <me>
            \textbf{Each Exterior Angle} = \frac{360}{7}
        </me>
        <me>
            =51.43^ \circ
        </me>
    </p><p>
        <m>\textbf{Study Questions}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        1. What is the sum of all interior angles of a heptagon ?    </p>
    <p>
        2. How do we calculate the measure of one interior angle of a regular heptagon ?    </p>
    <p>
       3. Can you find heptagons in real life? 
    </p>
      <example>
        <statement>
            <sidebyside>
             <p>
                A regular heptagon  measures 10 cm as indicated in the figure below, find its area given the sum of it's interior angles is<m>\, 900^\circ?</m>
            </p>
             <image>
            <latex-image label="regular-heptagon-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the heptagon
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:2);
                    }
                    
                    % Fill the heptagon with pink color
                    \fill[blue!45] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the heptagon
                    \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                    \coordinate(0,0);
                    \draw[thick] (P0) --(0,0) node[midway, above left]{10 cm};
                    \draw[fill=black](0,0) circle(2pt);
                    % Label the vertices
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \node[font=\small] at ({360/7*\i}:2.2) {$P_{\i}$};
                    }
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
           </image>
            </sidebyside>
           
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                There are 7 triangles since a heptagon has 7 sides.
                Area of Triangle <m>P_0OP_1 = \frac{1}{2} ab \, \text{sin }  \, 51.43^\circ </m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>  \triangle P_0OP_1 = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times 10\times 10\, \text{ sin} \,51.43^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times 100\, \text{cm}^2 \times \text{ sin } \, 51,43^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times 100\, \text{cm}^2 \times 0.7818 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 39.0923 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore the total area 
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp 7 \times 39.0923 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 273.65 \,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     
    </example>

</subsubsection>
      <subsubsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-an-octagon">
